value.value: Infection due to organisms from the genus Mycobacteria.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the pharynx. Representative examples include pharyngitis and carcinoma.

A benign hair follicle neoplasm with trichoblastic differentiation. It usually presents as a solitary papular lesion It most often presents on the head and neck area, but it may develop in any anatomic site containing hair follicles. Because of its benign nature, treatment usually is not required, provided that the diagnosis has been established with certainty.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder affecting the abducens nerve (sixth cranial nerve).
OBSOLETE. A disease or disorder that involves the retroperitoneal space.
An angiokeratoma that is located on the scrotum.
Deficiency of a coagulation factor that is not caused by genetic alterations. Causes include vitamin K deficiency, amyloidosis, and severe liver disease.
Viral encephalitis that is transmitted by mosquitos.
A rare genodermatosis with great phenotypic variation and characterized most commonly by ichthyosis, chondrodysplasia punctata (CDP), asymmetric shortening of the limbs, cataracts and short stature.
X-linked dominant form of disease.
X-linked recessive form of disease.

microcephaly, growth restriction and increased sister chromatid exchange

value.value: A malignant meningioma with aggressive clinical course. It recurs in approximately 50-78% of the cases. This category includes the anaplastic (malignant) meningioma, papillary meningioma, and rhabdoid meningioma.
A WHO grade III meningioma characterized by the presence of malignant morphologic features, including malignant cytology and a very high mitotic index (20 or more mitoses per ten high power fields).

A type of melanoma that typically occurs in light-skinned individuals ranging in age from young adults to the elderly. Risk factors include extensive sun exposure during childhood, a family history of melanoma, and the presence of dysplastic nevi.
A chromosomal abnormality consisting of the absence of one chromosome from the normal diploid number.
Inflammation of the brain secondary to an immune response triggered by the body itself.

A rare non-Hodgkin lymphoma that arises in and is confined to the lung at the time of diagnosis. Representative examples include bronchial mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue lymphoma and diffuse large B-cell lymphoma.
Autosomal dominant form of osteopetrosis (disease).

A non-Hodgkin lymphoma arising from the conjunctiva, lacrimal gland, lacrimal drainage apparatus, eyelids, or other orbital tissues around the eye. The vast majority of cases are extranodal marginal zone lymphomas of mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue, however, other histologic types of lymphomas can originate from ocular adnexal tissues, including rare cases of NK/T-cell lymphomas of nasal type.

germ cell tumor of the vulva
mixed germ cell tumor of vulva

value.value: An adenocarcinoma arising from the vagina. Morphologic variants include the clear cell, endometrioid, mesonephric, and mucinous adenocarcinoma.
A transitional cell carcinoma that arises from the renal pelvis and ureter.

label.value: human papillomavirus-related penile squamous cell carcinoma

value.value: A squamous cell carcinoma that arises from the penis and is caused by human papillomavirus infection. Morphologic variants include basaloid carcinoma and warty carcinoma.
A conventional osteosarcoma characterized by the predominance of osteoid matrix.
A malignant neoplasm characterized by the presence of atypical spindle cells.

label.value: Antley-Bixler syndrome without genital anomalies or disordered steroidogenesis

value.value: A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the paranasal sinuses.
A disorder characterized by occlusion of blood vessels. It differs from thrombosis in that it can be used to describe any form of blockage, not just one formed by a clot.
Complete closure of the normally patent lumen of the blood vessels which carry blood away from the heart.
Disease of the large or small intestine that is caused by inadequate blood supply.
Hearing loss caused by impaired transmission of signals from the external auditory canal or middle ear to the cochlea.
Acute inflammation of the bronchioles usually caused by the respiratory syncytial virus.
Disease having a short and relatively severe course.
An acute inflammation of the tonsils caused by viruses or bacteria. Signs and symptoms include fever, enlargement of the tonsils, difficulty swallowing, and enlargement of the regional lymph nodes.
An ependymal tumor arising from the supratentorial region of the brain.
